<div id="review_1451663037" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1451663037" />
    <a title="David Simms" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21797705-david-simms"><img alt="David Simms" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1530408695p2/21797705.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1451663037?book_show_action=true">Nov 25, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David Simms" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David Simms" href="/user/show/21797705-david-simms">David Simms</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1451663037" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4261701541073098079">Twisting My Kaleidoscope turned out to be an adventure that was something much more than expected. It&apos;s an important ride that readers in all genres need to take - not only is the quality of writing very strong, but the emotions drip from the page in a manner that is all heart and reflection without any melodrama that tends to flood many memoirs.<br/>As someone who has worked in mental health field as both a psychologist and special education teacher, the world of someone who has invasive disorder su</span>
  <span id="freeText4261701541073098079" style="display:none">Twisting My Kaleidoscope turned out to be an adventure that was something much more than expected. It's an important ride that readers in all genres need to take - not only is the quality of writing very strong, but the emotions drip from the page in a manner that is all heart and reflection without any melodrama that tends to flood many memoirs.<br />As someone who has worked in mental health field as both a psychologist and special education teacher, the world of someone who has invasive disorder such as psychosis, is a foreign land to the other 99% percent of the population. Shannon Love offers readers a glimpse into that land.<br />Love spins the tale of her life with the skill of a writer who knows her life and how to let it bleed onto the pages.<br />She had been enjoying her life with a husband and children in a comfortable, happy existence when her first psychotic break occurred. In another country. She begins a fight and journey that is fascinating to join as she opens up to doctors, psychiatrists, new friends, and the voices inside of her. Is the disorder which allows her sometimes a beautifully fractured view of her world a gift, or curse? Her family and friends struggle to help her survive her ordeal but she learns this is a marathon that last until her final breath. Learning to live with it becomes the goal along with keeping her family intact.<br />Love's descent, and then rise again into a new woman, is a beautiful story and one that will not disappoint. At its heart, Twisting My Kaleidoscope is a love story but much, much more. <br />Highly Recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4261701541073098079" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


