<div id="review_1603006436" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1603006436" />
    <a title="Charlie Vasquez" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/39800232-charlie-vasquez"><img alt="Charlie Vasquez" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1603006436?book_show_action=true">Apr 06, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Charlie Vasquez" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Charlie Vasquez" href="/user/show/39800232-charlie-vasquez">Charlie Vasquez</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1603006436" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1358142157301274227">I enjoy biographies, memoirs, true-life sort of books the most. So when I read the description and opening pages for “Twisting My Kaleidoscope: A Ticket into the World of Psychosis” by Shannon Love, I snatched it up hoping to learn more about a condition that affects countless people, but have never read much about, and I’m pleased to say that I was not disappointed. But while her story and journey is quite fascinating and meticulously detailed, and action-packed for a memoir, I felt at times th</span>
  <span id="freeText1358142157301274227" style="display:none">I enjoy biographies, memoirs, true-life sort of books the most. So when I read the description and opening pages for “Twisting My Kaleidoscope: A Ticket into the World of Psychosis” by Shannon Love, I snatched it up hoping to learn more about a condition that affects countless people, but have never read much about, and I’m pleased to say that I was not disappointed. But while her story and journey is quite fascinating and meticulously detailed, and action-packed for a memoir, I felt at times that it could have used more ‘tension’ to really thrust the story forward. Even during the ‘tense’ moments, it’s written in a way where we never really wonder if it will work out or not, and to me this is something that makes reading a better experience—if you are invested in the outcome and aren’t quite sure of things will be okay or not. But this was a really good book, and written with a powerful message that demands to be heard, and reminds us that with God and family we can make it through anything. Recommend for older teens on up and will appeal to readers of true-life drama and memoirs. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1358142157301274227" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


